The thing that&#x27;s nice about Linq is the integration. You can directly reference variables in the things you&#x27;re querying, and then either fill in an instance of an existing class, or generate an anonymous object.<p>For example:<p><pre><code>  var query = from c in customers
              join o in orders on c.ID equals o.ID
              select new {
                c.Name,
                o.Product,
                Address = c.MailingAddress
              };
</code></pre>
Of course, anonymous objects in C# can be a pain in the ass, since you can&#x27;t usefully return them from a method. Something like Scala&#x27;s structural types would solve that problem.<p>I don&#x27;t really like C# that much as a language, but I do like the Linq approach.
